{{Infobox Government agency |agency_name = Ministry of Education |nativename = {{Hebrew|'''משרד החינוך'''}} |abbreviation = |seal = |seal_width = |seal_caption = |picture = Italian hospital - ministry of education.JPG |picture_width = |picture_caption = Ministry of Education Headquarters |formed = 1949 |preceding1 = Ministry of Education, Culture and Sport |preceding2 = Ministry of Education and Culture |dissolved = |superseding = |jurisdiction = [[Government of Israel]] |employees = |budget = 42 billion [[New Shekel]]<ref>[http://www.financeisrael.mof.gov.il/FinanceIsrael/Docs/En/publications/StateBudgetProposal2013-2014.pdf State Budget Proposal for Fiscal Years 1023-1024] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131009231233/http://financeisrael.mof.gov.il/FinanceIsrael/Docs/En/publications/StateBudgetProposal2013-2014.pdf |date=2013-10-09 }} Ministry of Finance</ref> |headquarters = Lev Ram Building, [[Musrara, Jerusalem|Musrara]], [[Jerusalem]] |coordinates = {{coord|31|47|3.97|N|35|13|26.48|E|type:landmark_region:IS|display=inline,title}} |minister1_name = [[Naftali Bennett]] |minister1_pfo = |minister2_name = |minister2_pfo = |minister3_name = |minister3_pfo = |minister4_name = |minister4_pfo = |chief1_name = |chief1_position = |chief2_name = |chief2_position = |parent_agency = |child1_agency = |website = {{URL|http://cms.education.gov.il/}} |footnotes = }}
The [[Israel]]i '''Ministry of Education''' ({{lang-he-n|מִשְׂרָד הַחִנּוּךְ}}, [[Romanization of Hebrew|translit.]] ''Misrad HaHinukh''; {{lang-ar|وزارة التربية والتعليم}}) is the branch of government charged with overseeing public education institutions in Israel. The department is headed by the Minister of Education, who is a member of the [[cabinet of Israel|cabinet]]. The ministry has previously included culture and sport, although this is now covered by the [[Culture and Sport Ministry|Ministry of Culture and Sport]].
==History== [[File:PikiWiki Israel 13128 Ministry of Education in Jerusalem.jpg|thumb|250px|Ministry offices on [[Street of the Prophets]] in [[Jerusalem]]]] In the first decade of statehood, the education system was faced with the task of establishing a network of kindergartens and schools for a rapidly growing student population. In 1949, there were 80,000 elementary school students. By 1950, there were 120,000 - an increase of nearly 150 percent within the span of one year. Israel also took over responsibility for the education of Arab schoolchildren. The first minister of education was [[Zalman Shazar]], later president of the State of Israel.<ref>[https://books.google.co.il/books?id=VEUZbPc-h2gC&pg=PA58&lpg=PA58&dq=first+education+minister+israel&source=bl&ots=FLzeQN-VnC&sig=szav00hZlOHR53fUxxFdWnRerUg&hl=en&sa=X&ei=6smKVYnLBsjxUPG5mtgJ&ved=0CEMQ6AEwBjgo#v=onepage&q=first%20education%20minister%20israel&f=false The Retreat from Public Education: Global and Israeli Perspectives, Orit Ichilov]</ref> Since 2002, the Ministry of Education has awarded a [[National Education Award]] to five top localities in recognizing excellence in investing substantial resources in the educational system.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/153012#.T3OKN2FOAk0 | title = Shomron Regional Council Receives National Education Award | publisher = Israel National News | quote = “The award is an expression of our respect and appreciation for local authorities that are outstanding in the investment in education and in the importance they attach to fostering the local educational system.” | date=22 February 2012 | accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> In 2012, first place was awarded to the [[Shomron Regional Council]] and followed by [[Or Yehuda]], [[Tiberias]], [[Eilat]] and [[Beersheba]]. The prize has been awarded to a variety of educational institutions including kindergartens and elementary schools.
