{{Infobox book | name = | title_orig = | translator = | image = Seven Myths about Education.png | caption = | author = [[Daisy Christodoulou]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = | subject = | genre = Education | publisher = The Curriculum Centre, Routledge | pub_date = 2013 | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 133 | isbn = 978-0-415-74681-6 | dewey = | congress = | oclc = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''Seven Myths about Education''' is a book about education by [[Daisy Christodoulou]]. It suggests that [[declarative knowledge]] such as [[fact]]s is being neglected in modern education because of the priority given to [[procedural knowledge]] such as [[skill]]s.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/culture/books/non_fiction/article1385948.ece |title=Seven Myths About Education by Daisy Christodoulou |author=[[Dominic Lawson]] |date=16 March 2014 |newspaper=Sunday Times}}</ref> It was first published as an e-book by The Curriculum Centre in 2013 and then in hardback and paperback by [[Routledge]] in 2014.
The seven myths are:<ref name=G>{{citation |newspaper=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2014/nov/25/daisy-christodoulou-seven-myths-education-profile |author=Peter Wilby |date=25 November 2014 |title='Britain’s brightest student’ taking aim at teaching’s sacred cows}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/15582159.2014.942186?journalCode=wjsc20#.VathJ_lVhn8 |title=Review of Seven Myths about Education |author=Sandra Stotsky |journal=Journal of School Choice |volume=Vol. 8 |number=3 |year=2014 |doi=10.1080/15582159.2014.942186 |pages=530–532}}</ref>
:# Facts prevent [[understanding]] :# [[Teacher]]-led instruction is passive :# The 21st century fundamentally changes everything :# You can always just [[Google effect|look it up]] :# We should teach [[transferable skill]]s :# [[project-based learning|Projects]] and [[activity-based learning|activities]] are the best way to learn :# Teaching knowledge is [[indoctrination]].
